50 mm diameter piping from a manifold is
 used to transfer the CO2 to the eight chambers in which the
 CO2 concentration is elevated. The CO2 is introduced into
 the fan boxes through a perforated tube under suction
 provided by the fans, and is blown into the lower plenum
 of the chamber. A system of regulating the flow of CO2 into
 each chamber without feedback control is employed, using
 a valve situated on the CO2 supply pipe at the entry to each  fan box. This simple system is similar to that used by
 Drake et al. (1989).

column8: Liangyou 287 and Xiangfengyou 9 (early and late rice)
column21:
typical Chinese water regime (intermittent irrigation with mid-season drainage). Water could flow naturally between OTCs and the open field by
passing through holes at the bottom of the polycarbonate plates. During the rice growing period, fields were continuously flooded in the early stage, dried at the end of the tillering stage, with alternation of wetting and drying in the later stage, and drying of fields before harvest. The depth of flooded water was monitored manually with a straightedge every 1–2 days at 6 randomly selected sites.
column29: Heating and ventilation devices (consisting of a converter fan and resistance heating elements)
column34: An auto-induction control system (consisting of a display screen, single chip computers, sensors and relevant circuits) was employed to regulate atmospheric CO2 concentration and temperature inside the OTC and maintain constant operation.

In 2001, two N addition rates (i.e. 150 and
250 kgNha 1), hereinafter referred to as N150 and
N250, respectively, and one residue addition rate, (i.e.
approximately 1910 kgCha 1), hereinafter referred to
as HR, were applied for both elevated and ambient CO2
treatments.
In 2002, two N addition rates (i.e. N150 and N250),
and one residue addition rate (i.e. approximately
950 kgCha 1 (hereinafter referred to as MR)) were
applied. In the N150 plots, 1070 and 830 kg residue-
Cha 1 were applied under the elevated and ambient
CO2 conditions, respectively. In the N250 plots, 1040
and 860 kg residue-C ha 1 were amended under the
elevated and ambient CO2 conditions, respectively.
Each of the residue rates is equivalent to a half of the
carbon content in the harvested residue for a specific
treatment. The differences in the residue incorporation
rate were due to the actual harvested residue amount,
which could be affected by the elevated CO2 and
nitrogen amendments for the preceding wheat season.
In 2003, two N addition rates (i.e. N150 and N250)
were applied. Each plot receiving N150 treatment was
subdivided into subplots receiving residue at three
difference addition rates, i.e. 0, approximately 820
(exactly 900 kgCha 1 under the elevated CO2 and
730 kgCha 1 under the ambient), and 1850 kgCha 1,
hereinafter referred to as ZR, MR and HR, respectiv

column14: incubation experiments in the laboratory with laboratory and elevated CO2 concentration (1000 μl L–1) were carried out under flooded conditions at 25℃, 3 years after the FACE experiment with +200 ppm CO2 treatment.
column59: The incubation temperature was 25℃ and three replicates were conducted in this experiment. Twenty grams of prepared soil (air-dried basis) was placed in a 150 mL glass jar, flooded (about 2 cm above soil surface) by 30 mL deionized water, and then incubated at the laboratory (360–400 μl L–1) and the elevated CO2 concentrations (1000 μl L–1), respectively, at 25℃. During the incubation, CH4 and CO2 emissions were measured on days 0, 1, 3, 5, 7, 10, 13, 15, 17, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 47, 54 and 60. DOC was sampled devastatingly on days 0, 10, 15, 25, 40 and 60.

column21: Typical irrigation regimes of the surrounding areas were conducted. Each plot was randomly irrigated with nearby river water through agricultural irrigation ditches, submerged with water (about 5 cm in depth) from mid-June to mid-July, then drained several times to the beginning of August, and afterwards flooded with intermittent irrigation until 10 days before harvest.

column14: Details of the soil properties, climate and regional agricultural practices for the sites can be found in previous, related publications (Zheng et al., 2000; Kim et al., 2001, 2003; Inubushi et al., 2003; Xu et al., 2004).
column21: the rice paddies are flooded a few days before rice transplanting and during the early to mid-period of the rice-growing season. The rice paddies are drained during the late period of each rice season and kept dry during the nonrice season. Except for the two 1-week long periods of mid-season drainage about 5 and 9 weeks after the rice transplanting, the fields at the Chinese site were continuously flooded until the final drainage, which began about 85 days after transplanting (DAT). The final drainage at the Chinese site involved frequent flooding and draining up until about 2 weeks before harvest.
column34: the elevated atmospheric CO2 treatment was continuously applied in both rice- and wheatgrowing seasons, from mid-June 2001, when the rice season started, to mid-February 2004. The elevated CO2 treatment was, however, occasionally stopped during short fallow periods between the two crop-growing seasons.
column37: crop residue (wheat straw) and synthetic nitrogen added to the plots, ammonium based nitrogen
column38:
In 2001, two N addition rates (i.e. 150 and 250 kgNha 1), hereinafter referred to as N150 and N250, respectively, and one residue addition rate, (i.e. approximately 1910 kgCha 1), HR. In 2002, two N addition rates (i.e. N150 and N250), and one residue addition rate (i.e. approximately 950 kgCha 1 (hereinafter referred to as MR)) were applied. In the N150 plots, 1070 and 830 kg residue-
Cha 1 were applied under the elevated and ambient CO2 conditions, respectively. In the N250 plots, 1040 and 860 kg residue-C ha 1 were amended under the elevated and ambient CO2 conditions, respectively. In 2003, two N addition rates (i.e. N150 and N250) were applied.
column40: For N150, 60% of the fertilizer nitrogen was applied basally and 40% was top-dressed at late tillering. For N250, 36% was applied basally and 24% and 40% was top-dressed at early- and late-tillering, respectively. In the wheat cropping season before the first investigated rice season (2001), nitrogen fertilizers were applied at an equal rate of about 220 kgNha 1. In the wheat season before the second rice season (2002), nitrogen fertilizers were applied at 150 and 250 kgNha 1 in the plots receiving N150 and N250 treatments, respectively. In the wheat season before the third rice season (2003), nitrogen fertilizers were applied at 90 and 180 kgNha 1 in the plots receiving N150 and N250 treatments, respectively.

column21: A local water regime (F-D-F-M) of flooding midseason drainage-reflooding-intermittent moist irrigation was adopted for all the field plots. Specifically, flooding was started 3–5 days before transplanting, and continued for 30–35 days until an episode of the midseason drainage for 7–10 days. Thereafter, paddy field was re-flooded until 80–90 days after transplanting and followed by intermittent moist irrigation but without waterlogged for rice harvesting. The flooding water depth was kept at 5–8 cm during the period of waterlogging in rice paddies.

Twelve ceramic infrared heaters (IR) (2000 W, 240 V, 1.65 m long 0.14 m wide; HS-2420, Kalglo Electronics Co., Inc., Bethlehem, PA, USA) supplying 140 W/m2 of infrared radiation were equipped for each ring plot. column37: Urea (46% N) and compound fertilizer (15 N: 15 P2O5: 15 K2O) for N and compound fertilizer for P and K
column38: The fertilizers were applied four times during the rice season and three times during the wheat season. Urea was applied 2 days before rice transplanting and wheat seeding, at an average rate of 187.5 kg ha 1 as basal fertilizers. Compound fertilizer (375 kg ha 1 on average) was applied as topdressing after heading. Urea was applied two times in the rice season and once in the wheat season as topdressing fertilizer at an average rate of 150 kg ha 1. The basal fertilizer was thoroughly incorporated into the soil by ploughing to a depth of 10 cm, and the topdressing was surface broadcast.

column56: In 2012 rice season, ozone fumigation began on July 1 (10 days after transplanting (DAT)) and continued through to harvest. The seasonal 7-h mean [O3] (M7, 9:00–16:00) was 33.7 and 42.6 ppb (Fig. 1a), and AOT40 (accumulated daytime hourly [O3] above the threshold of 40 ppb) was 5.2 and 13.4 ppm h, for A-O3 and E-O3, respectively. Because the O3 release was discontinued under certain conditions as mentioned before, the effective increase in M7 and AOT40 was 26.7% and 160%, respectively. During the experimental period, the maximum hourly [O3] in E-O3 was 143.1 ppb, when [O3] was 91.9 ppb in A-O3.
